The Syndicates on chain rely on a mapping, so they are not iterable. Instead, it's necessary to search through an indexed lpAddress off-chain to get a list of an LP's Syndicates for screens such as the My Syndicates screen.This must be reconciled with lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate to get a list of all Syndicates that an LP is currently invested in."},"lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256,address,uint256)":{"details":"A separate event is emitted for withdrawing a distribution"},"lpWithdrewDistributionFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256,address,uint256)":{"details":"A separate event is emitted for withdrawing a deposit"},"memo(address,address,bytes32,bytes32,uint256)":{"details":"The memos are not stored within this contract directly, only via this event. Make sure this matches the token type (primary or secondary) passed in for claimedDistributions.","userContributions":"Total user has deposited to the fund"},"returns":{"_0":"Value in distributions that user is eligible to withdraw"}},"calculateProfitShare(uint256,uint256)":{"params":{"profitShareNumerator":"Establish fractional profit share (decimal %'s get messy fast). The profit share denominator is always PROFIT_SHARE_DENOMINATOR, which is set to 10000. Examples of different percentages can be found in the calculateProfitShare tests","withdrawal":"Total amount to user is sending"},"returns":{"_0":"Tuple of (withdrawalToUser, withdrawalToProfitShare) The withdrawal that the user will receive and the amount of the profit share that the Syndicate treasury (or, if adapted to asset management, the Syndicate manager) will receive during withdrawal"}},"closeSyndicate(address)":{"details":"Closing a Syndicate updates the closeDate to the current block timestamp This can be used for calculating management fees or determining how long the Syndicate has been deploying funds.","params":{"syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"confirmPendingManager(address)":{"params":{"syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"createSyndicate(address,uint256,uint256,uint256,uint256,bool)":{"details":"The rejectIfNotCurrentManager modifier is not necessary here since the Syndicate is being initialized and has not been created yetThis function is high risk. If a current Syndicate can be overwritten, someone could take control of the deposits by changing the current managerThe address of the Syndicate cannot be changed away from the msg.sender, but the manager address can be changed","params":{"allowlistEnabled":"False allows contributions to be sent without the manager needing to allow them. The manager can always reject a contribution before a Syndicate closes with `rejectLPInvestment()`","closeDate":"The date that the Syndicate will automatically close in UNIX time.","depositERC20ContractAddress":"The address of the ERC20 used for deposits (e.g. DAI or USDC's contract addresses) and withdrawals. Stablecoins are strongly recommended, especially for funds that are open for an extended period of time. (Otherwise one contributor might contribute one unit when a token is $100, and another contributor might contribute one unit when a token is $200, and they would have the same percentage ownership because they have both contributed one unit of a token. Stablecoins prevent this because the value is consistent.)","maxDeposit":"The max deposit per wallet address.","maxTotalDeposits":"The max deposit amount for the fund/Syndicate.","syndicateProfitSharePercent":"The profit share that is sent to the Syndicate treasury. Syndicate profit share adjusted by PERCENT_MULTIPLE (set to 10000 ether). For example, the minimum profit share of 0.30% should be passed in as 30 ether (since it is 0.30% * 10000 ether). This means that the max precision is 0.01%. There are helpful examples for common values in the calculateProfitShare within Syndicate.js."}},"denyAddress(address,address)":{"params":{"lpAddress":"The LP address that should be denied","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate that contains the allowlist"}},"emitMemo(address,bytes32,bytes32)":{"details":"For more on the recommendation to use `blake2b-328` hashes, see https://medium.com/temporal-cloud/efficient-usable-and-cheap-storage-of-ipfs-hashes-in-solidity-smart-contracts-eb3bef129eba","params":{"blake2b328HashPartOne":"The first 32 bytes of the hash","blake2b328HashPartTwo":"The second 32 bytes of the hash","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"getClaimedDistributions(address,address,address)":{"params":{"distributionERC20ContractAddress":"The address of the ERC20 to return the LP's claimed distributions","lpAddress":"The address of the LP whose info is being queried","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"},"returns":{"_0":"claimedDistributions by an LP for a given distributionERC20ContractAddress"}},"getSyndicateLPInfo(address,address)":{"details":"This function **must** be kept up to date with the Web3 UI when making changes. Functionality to transfer LP investments to new owners will likely be added in the future.","params":{"accredited":"Attestation that the LP is an accredited investor. Must be true to continue. This is to comply with SEC Rule 506(b) of Regulation D","amount":"The amount of the investment (note that this is calculated using the primary ERC20 token)","syndicateAddress":"The Syndicate address that the LP is investing in"}},"lpWithdrawFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256)":{"details":"Withdrawals are restricted to the primary or secondary ERC20 contract address. If we allowed any arbitrary ERC20 address, we would also need to track percentages for each arbitrary ERC20 address. This is significantly outside of the scope of the Syndicate contract and should be saved for future asset management contracts","params":{"amount":"The amount to withdraw","erc20ContractAddress":"The ERC 20 address to be transferred from the manager to the LP.","syndicateAddress":"The Syndicate that an LP wants to withdraw from"}},"owner()":{"details":"Returns the address of the current owner."},"paused()":{"details":"Returns true if the contract is paused, and false otherwise."},"rejectLPInvestment(address,address)":{"params":{"lpAddress":"The LP whose WHOLE contribution is being returned","syndicateAddress":"The Syndicate that the LP invested in"}},"setDistribution(address,address,uint256)":{"params":{"amount":"The amount of the distribution","distributionERC20Address":"The ERC20 contract address of the distribution","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"setManagerFeeAddress(address,address)":{"details":"The manager can burn the fees or send them to an address that they do not own if they'd like, there is no requirement that the managerFeeAddress cannot equal address(0) or e.g. the address of a charity","params":{"managerFeeAddress":"The address where manager fees should be sent. This cannot be the current or pending Syndicate manager","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"setManagerFees(address,uint256,uint256)":{"details":"Manager fees can only be set higher while the Syndicate is open to prevent managers from changing fees on LPs without the ability to act on those fee changes. The manager can only raise fees while LPs still have the ability to pull their money out. After the Syndicate is closed, fees can only be lowered and cannot be raised.In the future, we will include a timelock on all changes to raise fees. Since the current architecture requires trust in a manager because the manager holds the funds, this risk is one that we are willing to accept in the short-term.","params":{"managerManagementFeePercent":"The management fee of a Syndicate manager, calculated per year (e.g. 2% per year, which would be passed in as 200 ether because the fees are adjusted by PERCENT_MULTIPLE, which is set to 10000 ether. See the syndicateProfitShare documentation in `createSyndicate()` for more information on this calculation)","managerPerformanceFeePercent":"The performance fee of a Syndicate manager, received when an LP makes a withdrawal (e.g. 20% percent per distribution upon withdrawal, which would be passed in as 2000 ether)","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate to set fees for"}},"setPendingManager(address,address)":{"params":{"pendingManagerAddress":"The address of the new manager","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"setSyndicateInactiveStatus(address,bool)":{"params":{"inactiveStatus":"The boolean representing whether the Syndicate is inactive. Set inactiveStatus to true if the Syndicate is inactive. inactiveStatus is initialized to false upon creation of the Syndicate","syndicateAddress":"The address of the Syndicate"}},"transferOwnership(address)":{"details":"Transfers ownership of the contract to a new account (`newOwner`). Can only be called by the current owner."}},"title":"Syndicate management contract","version":1},"userdoc":{"events":{"lpInvestedInSyndicate(address,address,uint256,uint256)":{"notice":"Emit an event when an LP invests in a Syndicate"},"lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256,address,uint256)":{"notice":"Emit an event when an LP withdraws a deposit from a Syndicate. If an LP withdraws the full deposit that they originally invested, then they no longer have any holdings in a specific Syndicate"},"lpWithdrewDistributionFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256,address,uint256)":{"notice":"Emit an event when an LP withdraws a distribution from a Syndicate"},"memo(address,address,bytes32,bytes32,uint256)":{"notice":"Emit an event when a manager associates a memo with a Syndicate"}},"kind":"user","methods":{"allowAddresses(address,address[])":{"notice":"Used by a manager to add an array of LP addresses to the allowlistThere are two permission levels for a Syndicate:1. Addresses must be pre-approved by the manager and added to the allowlist before an LP can invest. These will have an event associated with them to allow for easy searching, but the event has not been created yet. This is when this function must be used.2. All addresses are allowed, and investments can be rejected after the fact. This is useful if you want to allow anyone to invest in a Syndicate (for example, for a non-profit might enable this because there is no expectation of profits and therefore they wouldn't need to be as concerned about approving every user who contributes to a Syndicate)Allowing addresses is unnecessary if you pass in setAutoConfirmDeposit(true). This enables the second permissions option, where all addresses are allowed by default and can be rejected after the fact with rejectLPInvestment. As a result, this function only can be used when the allowlist is enabled."},"calculateEligibleWithdrawal(uint256,uint256,uint256,uint256)":{"notice":"Calculates the maximum value in distribution tokens (in either primary or secondary ERC20) that an LP can withdraw based on their percentage ownership at the moment that the fund closed and the distributions that they have already received."},"closeSyndicate(address)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to close a Syndicate to new deposits.A Syndicate must be closed before distributions can be redeemed.Once a Syndicate is closed, it cannot be opened again. This is to prevent issues with redeeming distributions interacting with new deposits (e.g. a user with a 10% stake performs a withdrawal, and then a deposit occurs that dilutes them down to a 1% stake. From that point onward, they would only be entitled to 1% of the distributions)"},"confirmPendingManager(address)":{"notice":"Used by the pending manager to claim current manager statusThe pending manager is identified by `msg.sender`, which proves that they have control over their addressChanging a manager does not change the syndicateAddress. The syndicateAddress is permanent but has no effect beyond acting as an identifier."},"createSyndicate(address,uint256,uint256,uint256,uint256,bool)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to create a Syndicate with the address of the `msg.sender`"},"denyAddress(address,address)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to deny an address that has been previously added to the allowlistThis function only proceeds when the allowlist is enabled. A manager cannot deny an address when the allowlist is disabled since there is an incredible number of possible wallet addresses. Instead, a manager should use `rejectLPInvestment()`Denying an LP address that has previously been allowed does not reject an investment or return a contribution. The deposit is still kept in the SPV.All addresses are denied by default when an allowlist is enabled, so this is only necessary if you want to remove a previously allowed address"},"emitMemo(address,bytes32,bytes32)":{"notice":"Emit an event that references a memo stored as 64 byte hash.IPFS is recommended. If an IPFS hash is used, it must be `blake2b-328` so that it can be stored in 64 bytes.This can be used to store a fund thesis or describe a transaction that a fund manager made in their wallet. This provides transparency by notifying LPs of transactions and allowing them to verify the proper use of funds."},"getClaimedDistributions(address,address,address)":{"notice":"Get an LP's claimed distributions for a given ERC20"},"getSyndicateLPInfo(address,address)":{"notice":"Get the LP info for a SyndicateTo get the claimed distributiosn for another ERC20, use `getClaimedDistributions()`"},"getSyndicateMetadata(address,string)":{"notice":"Get the metadata for a given key within a Syndicate"},"getSyndicateValues(address)":{"notice":"Get the values for a Syndicate"},"getTotalDistributions(address,address)":{"notice":"Get Sydicate's total distributions per given ERC20"},"getUnclaimedDistributions(address,address,address)":{"notice":"Get an LP's unclaimed distribution for a given ERC20"},"lpInvestInSyndicate(address,uint256,bool)":{"notice":"Used by an LP to invest in a Syndicate"},"lpWithdrawFromSyndicate(address,address,uint256)":{"notice":"Used by an LP to withdraw a deposit or distribution from a SyndicateThe LP is identified via `msg.sender`. This call must be made from the LP address that originally called lpInvestInSyndicate until the functionality to transfer LP investments is addedWithdrawal options are different if the Syndicate is open or closed. If it is open, only the deposit ERC20 can be withdrawn. If it is closed and distributions are disabled, no ERC20s of any kind can be withdrawn. If it is closed and distributions are enabled, any ERC20 address can be withdrawn. Distributions are automatically enabled by the manager when they set a distribution for the first time."},"pauseContract()":{"notice":"Emergency pause function that can only be triggered by the contract ownerIts purpose is to pause deposits and withdrawals. All other functions will work when paused"},"rejectLPInvestment(address,address)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to reject an LP investmentThis is only used when the allowlist is disabled. When an allowlist is enabled, LPs have already been pre-approved so there is no need to reject investments. LPs should have certainty that their deposits are being accepted when the allowlist is enabled."},"renounceOwnership()":{"notice":"Renounce ownership of the contractUnpause the contract before ownership is renounced, to ensure that deposits/withdrawals are not locked"},"setDistribution(address,address,uint256)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to mark a distribution as availableIf this function is called before distributions are enabled, it will automatically enable distributions. Once enabled, distributions cannot be disabled.Distributions can be set for any ERC20 token, including the deposit tokenA sufficient allowance and balance must be set for the amount before this can proceed. The currentManager address must give an allowance greater than or equal to the distribution amount to the Syndicate contract address. Unlimited allowances are not recommended because they pose a security risk in case of a vulnerability in the contract.Managers only receive performance fees when a user withdraws a distribution, not when the manager sets the distribution. This prevents managers from setting a high allowance, taking their fee, and then cutting off the allowance and not allowing LPs to withdraw."},"setManagerFeeAddress(address,address)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to set the address where fees should be sent"},"setManagerFees(address,uint256,uint256)":{"notice":"Used by a manager to set their management and performance fees"},"setMaxDeposit(address,uint256)":{"notice":"Set the maximum total deposit a single LP can contribute to the fund"},"setMaxTotalDeposits(address,uint256)":{"notice":"Set the maximum amount that an SPV can receive in deposits"},"setPendingManager(address,address)":{"notice":"Used by the current manager to nominate a new managerThe current manager is pending until they claim the currentManager status. This ensures that the new current manager has control over their wallet and has also agreed to manage the fund.Changing a manager does not change the syndicateAddress. The syndicateAddress is permanent but has no effect beyond acting as an identifier.To reset a pendingManager request, just set the pendingManager to be address(0). @author Will Papper and Syndicate Inc.
 @title Syndicate management contract

@notice Emit an event when an LP withdraws a distribution from a Syndicate
 @dev A separate event is emitted for withdrawing a deposit
@notice Only proceed if the msg.sender is the current manager
@notice Only proceed if the Syndicate is open
@notice Only proceed if the Syndicate is closed
@notice Only proceed if the allowlist is enabled
@notice Only proceed if the allowlist is disabled

@notice Set the maximum total deposit a single LP can contribute to the
 fund
@notice Set the maximum amount that an SPV can receive in deposits

@notice Only proceed if the LP attests that they are an accredited
 investor. This is to comply with SEC Rule 506(b) of Regulation D
 @notice Under Rule 506(b), up to 35 non-accredited investors can invest
 in a private placement. These non-accredited investors must have
 sufficient knowledge and experience, which is difficult to verify in a
 decentralized context. As a result, we leave it up to the Syndicate
 manager to track their own list of up to 35 non-accredited investors and
 add them to the allowlist. The Syndicate manager must provide disclosures
 to non-accredited investors that comply with Regulation A offerings, give
 non-accredited investors financial statement information specified in
 Rule 506, and be avaialble to answer questions from potential LPs who are
 non-accredited investors. This responsibility rests with the Syndicate
 manager. See https://www.sec.gov/smallbusiness/exemptofferings/rule506b
 @notice Nothing in this documentation should be considered legal
 advice. If you are seeking any clarification, please email us at
 hello[at]syndicateprotocol.org.
@notice Only proceed if distributions have not been enabled
@notice Only proceed after distributions have been enabled

lpInvestedInSyndicate(address,address,ui.details: This is the only way to search for an LP's Syndicates. The Syndicates on chain rely on a mapping, so they are not iterable. Instead, it's necessary to search through an indexed lpAddress off-chain to get a list of an LP's Syndicates for screens such as the My Syndicates screen.This must be reconciled with lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate to get a list of all Syndicates that an LP is currently invested in.

lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate(address,a.details: A separate event is emitted for withdrawing a distribution

lpWithdrewDistributionFromSyndicate(addr.details: A separate event is emitted for withdrawing a deposit

memo(address,address,bytes32,bytes32,uin.details: The memos are not stored within this contract directly, only via this event. They are not recorded within the struct. If a manager wants to store a value within the struct, they should use `setMetadata()`

allowAddresses(address,address[]).details: Allowing a single address costs 31527 in gas without an array and 32445 in gas with an array. This is a difference in cost of $0.17 at current gas prices, which is a worthwhile trade off considering that (a) allowing only one address will be less common than allowing multiple addresses and (b) having two different allowAddress functions poses a security risk if we forget to reconcile changes between them

params.lpAddresses: An array of addresses to be allowed by the Syndicate
params.syndicateAddress: The address of the Syndicate that will accept the allowedAdresses

calculateEligibleWithdrawal(uint256,uint.details: HIGH RISK: If this calculation is incorrect, a user could withdraw more or less than they are entitled to.

params.claimedDistributions: Value in distributions that user has withdrawn from the fund already.  Make sure this matches the token type (primary or secondary) passed in for totalDistributions.
params.totalContributions: Total contributions (from anyone) to the fund
params.totalDistributions: Total distributions available from the fund, claimed or not.  Make sure this matches the token type (primary or secondary) passed in for claimedDistributions.
params.userContributions: Total user has deposited to the fund

returns._0: Value in distributions that user is eligible to withdraw

params.profitShareNumerator: Establish fractional profit share (decimal %'s get messy fast). The profit share denominator is always PROFIT_SHARE_DENOMINATOR, which is set to 10000. Examples of different percentages can be found in the calculateProfitShare tests
params.withdrawal: Total amount to user is sending

returns._0: Tuple of (withdrawalToUser, withdrawalToProfitShare) The withdrawal that the user will receive and the amount of the profit share that the Syndicate treasury (or, if adapted to asset management, the Syndicate manager) will receive during withdrawal

closeSyndicate(address).details: Closing a Syndicate updates the closeDate to the current block timestamp This can be used for calculating management fees or determining how long the Syndicate has been deploying funds.

createSyndicate(address,uint256,uint256,.details: The rejectIfNotCurrentManager modifier is not necessary here since the Syndicate is being initialized and has not been created yetThis function is high risk. If a current Syndicate can be overwritten, someone could take control of the deposits by changing the current managerThe address of the Syndicate cannot be changed away from the msg.sender, but the manager address can be changed

params.allowlistEnabled: False allows contributions to be sent without the manager needing to allow them. The manager can always reject a contribution before a Syndicate closes with `rejectLPInvestment()`
params.closeDate: The date that the Syndicate will automatically close in UNIX time.
params.depositERC20ContractAddress: The address of the ERC20 used for deposits (e.g. DAI or USDC's contract addresses) and withdrawals. Stablecoins are strongly recommended, especially for funds that are open for an extended period of time. (Otherwise one contributor might contribute one unit when a token is $100, and another contributor might contribute one unit when a token is $200, and they would have the same percentage ownership because they have both contributed one unit of a token. Stablecoins prevent this because the value is consistent.)
params.maxDeposit: The max deposit per wallet address.
params.maxTotalDeposits: The max deposit amount for the fund/Syndicate.
params.syndicateProfitSharePercent: The profit share that is sent to the Syndicate treasury. Syndicate profit share adjusted by PERCENT_MULTIPLE (set to 10000 ether). For example, the minimum profit share of 0.30% should be passed in as 30 ether (since it is 0.30% * 10000 ether). This means that the max precision is 0.01%. There are helpful examples for common values in the calculateProfitShare within Syndicate.js.

params.lpAddress: The LP address that should be denied
params.syndicateAddress: The address of the Syndicate that contains the allowlist

emitMemo(address,bytes32,bytes32).details: For more on the recommendation to use `blake2b-328` hashes, see https://medium.com/temporal-cloud/efficient-usable-and-cheap-storage-of-ipfs-hashes-in-solidity-smart-contracts-eb3bef129eba

params.blake2b328HashPartOne: The first 32 bytes of the hash
params.blake2b328HashPartTwo: The second 32 bytes of the hash

params.distributionERC20ContractAddress: The address of the ERC20 to return the LP's claimed distributions
params.lpAddress: The address of the LP whose info is being queried

returns._0: claimedDistributions by an LP for a given distributionERC20ContractAddress

getSyndicateLPInfo(address,address).details: This function **must** be kept up to date with the Web3 UI when making changes. All PRs that change this function **must** be coordinated with an engineer on the Web3 Dashboard.

params.lpAddress: The address of the LP whose info is being queried

params.metadataKey: The string that is the key of the metadata to look up

getSyndicateValues(address).details: This function **must** be kept up to date with the web3 UI when making changes. All PRs that change this function **must** be coordinated with an engineer on the Web3 Dashboard.

params.distributionERC20ContractAddress: The address of the ERC20 to return total distributions
The address of the ERC20 to return the LP's unclaimed distributions
params.lpAddress: The address of the LP whose info is being queried

returns._0: unclaimedDistributions by an LP for a given distributionERC20ContractAddress

lpInvestInSyndicate(address,uint256,bool.details: The LP's investment is tied to their current address via `msg.sender`. Functionality to transfer LP investments to new owners will likely be added in the future.

params.accredited: Attestation that the LP is an accredited investor. Must be true to continue. This is to comply with SEC Rule 506(b) of Regulation D
params.amount: The amount of the investment (note that this is calculated using the primary ERC20 token)
params.syndicateAddress: The Syndicate address that the LP is investing in

lpWithdrawFromSyndicate(address,address,.details: Withdrawals are restricted to the primary or secondary ERC20 contract address. If we allowed any arbitrary ERC20 address, we would also need to track percentages for each arbitrary ERC20 address. This is significantly outside of the scope of the Syndicate contract and should be saved for future asset management contracts

params.erc20ContractAddress: The ERC 20 address to be transferred from the manager to the LP.
params.syndicateAddress: The Syndicate that an LP wants to withdraw from

owner().details: Returns the address of the current owner.

paused().details: Returns true if the contract is paused, and false otherwise.

params.lpAddress: The LP whose WHOLE contribution is being returned
params.syndicateAddress: The Syndicate that the LP invested in

params.distributionERC20Address: The ERC20 contract address of the distribution

setManagerFeeAddress(address,address).details: The manager can burn the fees or send them to an address that they do not own if they'd like, there is no requirement that the managerFeeAddress cannot equal address(0) or e.g. the address of a charity

params.managerFeeAddress: The address where manager fees should be sent. This cannot be the current or pending Syndicate manager

setManagerFees(address,uint256,uint256).details: Manager fees can only be set higher while the Syndicate is open to prevent managers from changing fees on LPs without the ability to act on those fee changes. The manager can only raise fees while LPs still have the ability to pull their money out. After the Syndicate is closed, fees can only be lowered and cannot be raised.In the future, we will include a timelock on all changes to raise fees. Since the current architecture requires trust in a manager because the manager holds the funds, this risk is one that we are willing to accept in the short-term.

params.managerManagementFeePercent: The management fee of a Syndicate manager, calculated per year (e.g. 2% per year, which would be passed in as 200 ether because the fees are adjusted by PERCENT_MULTIPLE, which is set to 10000 ether. See the syndicateProfitShare documentation in `createSyndicate()` for more information on this calculation)
params.managerPerformanceFeePercent: The performance fee of a Syndicate manager, received when an LP makes a withdrawal (e.g. 20% percent per distribution upon withdrawal, which would be passed in as 2000 ether)
params.syndicateAddress: The address of the Syndicate to set fees for

params.pendingManagerAddress: The address of the new manager

params.inactiveStatus: The boolean representing whether the Syndicate is inactive. Set inactiveStatus to true if the Syndicate is inactive. inactiveStatus is initialized to false upon creation of the Syndicate

transferOwnership(address).details: Transfers ownership of the contract to a new account (`newOwner`). Can only be called by the current owner.

lpInvestedInSyndicate(address,address,ui.notice: Emit an event when an LP invests in a Syndicate

lpWithdrewDepositFromSyndicate(address,a.notice: Emit an event when an LP withdraws a deposit from a Syndicate. If an LP withdraws the full deposit that they originally invested, then they no longer have any holdings in a specific Syndicate

lpWithdrewDistributionFromSyndicate(addr.notice: Emit an event when an LP withdraws a distribution from a Syndicate

memo(address,address,bytes32,bytes32,uin.notice: Emit an event when a manager associates a memo with a Syndicate

allowAddresses(address,address[]).notice: Used by a manager to add an array of LP addresses to the allowlistThere are two permission levels for a Syndicate:1. Addresses must be pre-approved by the manager and added to the allowlist before an LP can invest. These will have an event associated with them to allow for easy searching, but the event has not been created yet. This is when this function must be used.2. All addresses are allowed, and investments can be rejected after the fact. This is useful if you want to allow anyone to invest in a Syndicate (for example, for a non-profit might enable this because there is no expectation of profits and therefore they wouldn't need to be as concerned about approving every user who contributes to a Syndicate)Allowing addresses is unnecessary if you pass in setAutoConfirmDeposit(true). This enables the second permissions option, where all addresses are allowed by default and can be rejected after the fact with rejectLPInvestment. As a result, this function only can be used when the allowlist is enabled.

calculateEligibleWithdrawal(uint256,uint.notice: Calculates the maximum value in distribution tokens (in either primary or secondary ERC20) that an LP can withdraw based on their percentage ownership at the moment that the fund closed and the distributions that they have already received.

closeSyndicate(address).notice: Used by a manager to close a Syndicate to new deposits.A Syndicate must be closed before distributions can be redeemed.Once a Syndicate is closed, it cannot be opened again. This is to prevent issues with redeeming distributions interacting with new deposits (e.g. a user with a 10% stake performs a withdrawal, and then a deposit occurs that dilutes them down to a 1% stake. From that point onward, they would only be entitled to 1% of the distributions)

confirmPendingManager(address).notice: Used by the pending manager to claim current manager statusThe pending manager is identified by `msg.sender`, which proves that they have control over their addressChanging a manager does not change the syndicateAddress. The syndicateAddress is permanent but has no effect beyond acting as an identifier.

createSyndicate(address,uint256,uint256,.notice: Used by a manager to create a Syndicate with the address of the `msg.sender`

denyAddress(address,address).notice: Used by a manager to deny an address that has been previously added to the allowlistThis function only proceeds when the allowlist is enabled. A manager cannot deny an address when the allowlist is disabled since there is an incredible number of possible wallet addresses. Instead, a manager should use `rejectLPInvestment()`Denying an LP address that has previously been allowed does not reject an investment or return a contribution. The deposit is still kept in the SPV.All addresses are denied by default when an allowlist is enabled, so this is only necessary if you want to remove a previously allowed address

emitMemo(address,bytes32,bytes32).notice: Emit an event that references a memo stored as 64 byte hash.IPFS is recommended. If an IPFS hash is used, it must be `blake2b-328` so that it can be stored in 64 bytes.This can be used to store a fund thesis or describe a transaction that a fund manager made in their wallet. This provides transparency by notifying LPs of transactions and allowing them to verify the proper use of funds.

getClaimedDistributions(address,address,.notice: Get an LP's claimed distributions for a given ERC20

getSyndicateLPInfo(address,address).notice: Get the LP info for a SyndicateTo get the claimed distributiosn for another ERC20, use `getClaimedDistributions()`

getSyndicateMetadata(address,string).notice: Get the metadata for a given key within a Syndicate

getSyndicateValues(address).notice: Get the values for a Syndicate

getTotalDistributions(address,address).notice: Get Sydicate's total distributions per given ERC20

getUnclaimedDistributions(address,addres.notice: Get an LP's unclaimed distribution for a given ERC20

lpInvestInSyndicate(address,uint256,bool.notice: Used by an LP to invest in a Syndicate

lpWithdrawFromSyndicate(address,address,.notice: Used by an LP to withdraw a deposit or distribution from a SyndicateThe LP is identified via `msg.sender`. This call must be made from the LP address that originally called lpInvestInSyndicate until the functionality to transfer LP investments is addedWithdrawal options are different if the Syndicate is open or closed. If it is open, only the deposit ERC20 can be withdrawn. If it is closed and distributions are disabled, no ERC20s of any kind can be withdrawn. If it is closed and distributions are enabled, any ERC20 address can be withdrawn. Distributions are automatically enabled by the manager when they set a distribution for the first time.

pauseContract().notice: Emergency pause function that can only be triggered by the contract ownerIts purpose is to pause deposits and withdrawals. All other functions will work when paused

rejectLPInvestment(address,address).notice: Used by a manager to reject an LP investmentThis is only used when the allowlist is disabled. When an allowlist is enabled, LPs have already been pre-approved so there is no need to reject investments. LPs should have certainty that their deposits are being accepted when the allowlist is enabled.

renounceOwnership().notice: Renounce ownership of the contractUnpause the contract before ownership is renounced, to ensure that deposits/withdrawals are not locked

setDistribution(address,address,uint256).notice: Used by a manager to mark a distribution as availableIf this function is called before distributions are enabled, it will automatically enable distributions. Once enabled, distributions cannot be disabled.Distributions can be set for any ERC20 token, including the deposit tokenA sufficient allowance and balance must be set for the amount before this can proceed. The currentManager address must give an allowance greater than or equal to the distribution amount to the Syndicate contract address. Unlimited allowances are not recommended because they pose a security risk in case of a vulnerability in the contract.Managers only receive performance fees when a user withdraws a distribution, not when the manager sets the distribution. This prevents managers from setting a high allowance, taking their fee, and then cutting off the allowance and not allowing LPs to withdraw.

setManagerFeeAddress(address,address).notice: Used by a manager to set the address where fees should be sent

setManagerFees(address,uint256,uint256).notice: Used by a manager to set their management and performance fees

setMaxDeposit(address,uint256).notice: Set the maximum total deposit a single LP can contribute to the fund

setMaxTotalDeposits(address,uint256).notice: Set the maximum amount that an SPV can receive in deposits

setPendingManager(address,address).notice: Used by the current manager to nominate a new managerThe current manager is pending until they claim the currentManager status. This ensures that the new current manager has control over their wallet and has also agreed to manage the fund.Changing a manager does not change the syndicateAddress. The syndicateAddress is permanent but has no effect beyond acting as an identifier.To reset a pendingManager request, just set the pendingManager to be address(0). This is the value that it is initialized at within the SingleSyndicate struct (it is the default value for all addresses)

setSyndicateInactiveStatus(address,bool).notice: Used by a manager to mark a Syndicate as inactive or activeThis signals that the Syndicate is no longer in use. This only changes the UI that end users see and has no implications for the operation of the smart contract. If a manager would like to shut down a Syndicate, they should close the Syndicate and enable distributions.

unPauseContract().notice: Emergency unpause function that can only be triggered by the contract ownerIts purpose is to unpause deposits and withdrawals. All other functions will work when paused
